\begin{document}

\title{Structuring LLM Arguments:\\
A Typed Attack Candidate Approach\\
for Dung Abstract Argumentation Frameworks}

\titlerunning{Typed LLM Attack Extraction for Dung AFs}

\author{A. Habyarimana}
\authorrunning{A. Habyarimana}
\institute{Johannes Gutenberg-Universität Mainz, Mainz, Germany\\
\email{ahabyari@students.uni-mainz.de}}

\maketitle

\begin{abstract}
This document describes the current state of an LLM-based argument mining
pipeline that extracts Dung Abstract Argumentation Frameworks (AAFs) from
natural-language debate texts. Rather than treating attack detection as a
binary classification task, the system prompts a Large Language Model to
produce \emph{typed attack candidates} — each annotated with an attack
type (rebuttal, undercutting, or undermining), a numerical confidence
score (used as a routing signal, not a calibrated probability), and a natural-language justification. A two-stage confidence filter
selects candidates; accepted candidates are collapsed to binary Dung
\texttt{att/2} facts and evaluated in Prolog under grounded, preferred,
and stable semantics. The document is intended as a technical reference
for the supervisors and describes the pipeline in detail, including
pseudocode, design decisions, and example outputs from a run on the UKP
nuclear energy debate corpus.

\keywords{Argument Mining \and Dung AAF \and Large Language Models
\and Attack Typology \and UKP Corpus}
\end{abstract}

\section{Introduction}

The goal of this project is to connect two fields that have largely
developed in parallel: \emph{argument mining} (identifying argumentative
structure in natural text) and \emph{formal argumentation} (computing
acceptable positions from an attack graph).

The core idea is simple: if we can identify which arguments attack which
others in a debate, we obtain a Dung Abstract Argumentation
Framework~\cite{dung1995} for free. A Prolog solver then computes which
arguments survive under various semantics — without any further LLM
involvement. The formal result can then be compared with a direct
``what do you find convincing?'' query to the same LLM, revealing whether
the LLM's own intuitions agree with the formal consequences of the attacks
it identified.

The key methodological decision in this project is \textbf{not} to ask the
LLM a binary yes/no question per argument pair. Instead, the LLM proposes
a structured \emph{attack candidate} that includes: (1) an attack type
drawn from Pollock's typology~\cite{pollock1992}, (2) a confidence score,
and (3) a one-sentence justification. This richer output improves the
quality of the extraction and makes the system's reasoning transparent and
auditable.

\section{Background}
\subsection{Dung Abstract Argumentation Frameworks}

A Dung AAF~\cite{dung1995} is a pair $AF = \langle \mathcal{A},
\mathcal{R} \rangle$ where $\mathcal{A}$ is a finite set of arguments
and $\mathcal{R} \subseteq \mathcal{A} \times \mathcal{A}$ is a binary
attack relation. The internal structure of arguments is irrelevant —
only the graph matters for computing extensions.

A set $S \subseteq \mathcal{A}$ is \emph{conflict-free} if no member
attacks another. Argument $a$ is \emph{defended} by $S$ if every
attacker of $a$ is attacked by some member of $S$. Three standard
semantics are used in this project:

\begin{itemize}
  \item \textbf{Grounded extension:} the unique least fixed point of
    $F_{AF}(S) = \{a \in \mathcal{A} \mid S \text{ defends } a\}$,
    computed by iterating from the empty set. Always exists and is unique.
  \item \textbf{Preferred extensions:} maximal admissible sets (conflict-free
    and self-defending). May be multiple.
  \item \textbf{Stable extensions:} conflict-free sets that attack every
    non-member. May not exist.
\end{itemize}

\subsection{Attack Typology}
\label{sec:taxonomy}

Dung's framework is \emph{abstract}: it does not distinguish why one
argument attacks another. Pollock~\cite{pollock1992} and later
ASPIC+~\cite{modgil2014} identify three qualitatively distinct attack
types in natural-language debate:

\begin{description}
  \item[Rebuttal] The attacker directly contradicts the \emph{conclusion}
    of the target. This is the strongest form of attack — it directly
    denies what the target claims.
    \begin{quote}\small
      \emph{pro:} ``Nuclear energy is a clean energy source.''\\
      \emph{con attacks via rebuttal:} ``Nuclear plants produce
      catastrophic environmental contamination.''
    \end{quote}
  \item[Undercutting] The attacker shows that the target's conclusion
    does not follow from its premises, even if those premises are true.
    The inference step is attacked, not the conclusion directly.
    \begin{quote}\small
      \emph{pro:} ``Newer reactor designs are safer, so nuclear is
      acceptable.''\\
      \emph{pro attacks via undercutting:} ``Even newer designs show
      that safety improvements do not generalise — Chernobyl-era
      reactors were also considered safe in their time.''
    \end{quote}
  \item[Undermining] The attacker targets a \emph{premise} the target
    relies on, without directly engaging the conclusion.
    \begin{quote}\small
      \emph{pro:} ``Nuclear plants have robust containment structures,
      so they are safe.''\\
      \emph{con attacks via undermining:} ``Nuclear waste is hard to
      manage and radiation cannot be contained indefinitely.''
      (attacks the premise that containment is sufficient)
    \end{quote}
\end{description}

All three types collapse to a single \texttt{att(A,B)} in Dung's
framework. Section~\ref{sec:collapsing} discusses this design decision.

\subsection{Dataset: UKP Sentential Argument Mining Corpus}

The pipeline is evaluated on the UKP Sentential Argument Mining
Corpus~\cite{stab2014}, which provides sentence-level stance annotations
for eight controversial topics. Table~\ref{tab:ukp} shows the corpus
statistics for the topic used in initial experiments.

\begin{table}[t]
\caption{UKP corpus statistics for \emph{Nuclear Energy}.}
\label{tab:ukp}
\centering
\begin{tabular}{lrrrr}
\toprule
Topic & Sentences & Documents & Total Args & Pro / Con \\
\midrule
Nuclear Energy & 6{,}261 & 144 & 2{,}469 & 354 / 742 \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{table}

Each sentence is labelled \texttt{Argument\_for}, \texttt{Argument\_against},
or \texttt{NoArgument}. The pipeline loads only labelled arguments
(discarding \texttt{NoArgument}) and uses the \texttt{test} split.

