\subsection{Step 0a/b: Argument Acquisition}

\paragraph{UKP source.} Arguments are loaded from the corpus TSV files.
Only rows with annotation \texttt{Argument\_for} or
\texttt{Argument\_against} are kept. A balanced sample (equal pro/con) is
drawn with a fixed random seed for reproducibility. Each argument is
represented as a Python dictionary:

\begin{lstlisting}[style=json]
{"id": "pro5", "text": "Nuclear power can provide ...", "stance": "pro"}
\end{lstlisting}

\paragraph{LLM source.} Alternatively, arguments are generated by prompting
the LLM to produce $n_{\text{pro}}$ pro and $n_{\text{con}}$ con arguments
about a given topic in the same JSON format.

\subsection{Step 0c: Argument Atomisation}

Natural-language arguments frequently bundle multiple claims. A compound
sentence like ``Although nuclear energy produces waste, it is cleaner than
coal'' contains a concession and a main claim — the concession is a
rhetorical hedge, not a standalone argument.

The atomisation step uses an LLM to split each argument into atomic
claims — those that express exactly one evaluative position. The prompt
enforces three rules:

\begin{enumerate}
  \item \textbf{Drop concessive fragments.} Anything introduced by
    ``Although'', ``While'', ``Despite'', etc.\ is dropped.
  \item \textbf{Resolve pronouns.} Any fragment containing ``it'',
    ``they'', ``this'' without a recoverable referent is either resolved
    or dropped.
  \item \textbf{Filter non-argumentative content.} Pure factual statements
    without an evaluative stance are removed.
\end{enumerate}

Algorithm~\ref{alg:atomise} shows the procedure. In practice, roughly
half of UKP sentences are split into 2 atomic arguments.

\begin{algorithm}[t]
\caption{Argument Atomisation}
\label{alg:atomise}
\begin{algorithmic}[1]
\Require argument list $\mathcal{A}$, topic $T$
\Ensure atomised list $\mathcal{A}'$
\State $\mathcal{A}' \gets []$
\For{each $a \in \mathcal{A}$ \textbf{in parallel}}
  \State $\textit{atoms} \gets \mathrm{LLM\_atomise}(a, T)$
    \Comment{returns $\geq 1$ atomic args}
  \State append $\textit{atoms}$ to $\mathcal{A}'$
\EndFor
\State fix ID conflicts in $\mathcal{A}'$
  \Comment{e.g.\ \texttt{pro5} $\to$ \texttt{pro5}, \texttt{pro5b}}
\Return $\mathcal{A}'$
\end{algorithmic}
\end{algorithm}

\subsection{Step 1: Typed Attack Candidate Extraction}
\label{sec:extraction}

This is the central contribution of the pipeline. Instead of asking the
LLM ``does $A$ attack $B$?'' (binary), the prompt asks it to
\emph{propose a typed attack candidate} with the following fields:

\begin{lstlisting}[style=json]
{
  "pair":        "pro55:con72",
  "direction":   "A_ATTACKS_B | B_ATTACKS_A | NONE",
  "attack_type": "rebuttal | undercutting | undermining | NONE",
  "confidence":  <integer 0--100>,
  "reason":      "<one-sentence justification>"
}
\end{lstlisting}

The prompt provides the full definitions of all three attack types
(Section~\ref{sec:taxonomy}) and enforces: \emph{if
\texttt{direction=NONE} then \texttt{attack\_type=NONE} and
\texttt{confidence=0}}. Mutual attacks (\texttt{MUTUAL}) are
not a valid direction value; if both directions hold, the LLM
is expected to return two separate candidates — one per direction
— in subsequent pair orderings (see Section~\ref{sec:design}).

\paragraph{Batching.} All $\binom{|\mathcal{A}'|}{2}$ argument pairs are
grouped into batches of size $b=10$ and submitted as a single API call
each. This reduces the number of API calls from $O(n^2)$ to
$O(n^2 / b)$. Pairs for which the LLM returns malformed JSON are retried
once as individual calls.

Algorithm~\ref{alg:extract} shows the extraction procedure.

\begin{algorithm}[t]
\caption{Typed Attack Candidate Extraction}
\label{alg:extract}
\begin{algorithmic}[1]
\Require atomised arguments $\mathcal{A}'$, topic $T$, batch size $b$
\Ensure candidate dict $C$: $(a_i, a_j) \to \textit{candidate}$
\State $\textit{pairs} \gets \{(a_i, a_j) \mid i < j,\; \mathrm{base}(a_i) \neq \mathrm{base}(a_j)\}$
\State $C \gets \emptyset$
\State $\textit{batches} \gets \mathrm{chunk}(\textit{pairs}, b)$
\For{each $\textit{batch} \in \textit{batches}$ \textbf{in parallel}}
  \State $\textit{raw} \gets \mathrm{LLM\_batch}(\textit{batch}, T)$
  \If{valid JSON list}
    \State insert results into $C$
  \Else
    \State retry batch; then fall back to individual calls
  \EndIf
\EndFor
\Return $C$
\end{algorithmic}
\end{algorithm}

\paragraph{Why typed candidates?} The type annotation guides the LLM's
own reasoning: by being asked to \emph{justify which type applies}, the
model is forced to engage with the argumentative content rather than
pattern-matching on surface cues such as opposite stances. The reason
field provides an auditable trace for each decision.

\subsection{Step 2: Confidence Filtering and Verification}

Candidates are routed through a three-way decision based on their
reported confidence $c$:

\begin{equation}
\text{decision}(c) = \begin{cases}
  \textbf{ACCEPT} & c \geq \theta_{\text{acc}} = 70 \\
  \textbf{VERIFY} & \theta_{\text{ver}} \leq c < \theta_{\text{acc}},
                    \quad \theta_{\text{ver}} = 50 \\
  \textbf{REJECT} & c < \theta_{\text{ver}}
\end{cases}
\end{equation}

Candidates in the \textbf{VERIFY} region are submitted to a second
LLM call (the \emph{verifier}) that answers: ``Does this attack
relation genuinely hold?'' and returns \texttt{\{"confirms": true/false,
"reason": "..."\}}. A verified candidate is accepted; an unconfirmed
one is rejected. Note that the verifier uses the same underlying model
as the extractor; genuine independence is not guaranteed — the step
provides a different prompt framing, not a different knowledge base.

Table~\ref{tab:filter} illustrates the three outcomes with real examples
from the nuclear energy run.

\begin{table}[t]
\caption{Example filter outcomes from the nuclear energy run (10 UKP
  arguments, 30 atoms after atomisation).}
\label{tab:filter}
\centering\small
\begin{tabular}{llcll}
\toprule
Pair & Direction & Conf & Type & Outcome \\
\midrule
pro55 $\leftrightarrow$ con72  & B\_ATTACKS\_A & 80 & undermining & ACCEPT \\
pro106 $\leftrightarrow$ con42 & B\_ATTACKS\_A & 95 & rebuttal    & ACCEPT \\
pro62b $\leftrightarrow$ con126 & B\_ATTACKS\_A & 90 & rebuttal   & ACCEPT \\
pro55b $\leftrightarrow$ con72  & B\_ATTACKS\_A & 65 & undermining & REJECT (verify denied) \\
pro27 $\leftrightarrow$ con72   & B\_ATTACKS\_A & 60 & undermining & REJECT (verify denied) \\
pro62 $\leftrightarrow$ pro106  & A\_ATTACKS\_B & 60 & undermining & REJECT (verify denied) \\
pro5b $\leftrightarrow$ con72   & NONE          & 10 & NONE        & SKIP \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{table}

\subsection{Step 3a: Collapsing to Dung}
\label{sec:collapsing}

Accepted candidates — each a rich record $\langle A, B,
\textit{type}, c, r \rangle$ — are reduced to binary Dung facts:

\begin{equation}
  \langle A, B, \textit{type}, c, r \rangle \;\longmapsto\; \texttt{att}(A,\, B).
\end{equation}

This is a \textbf{deliberate design decision}. Three alternatives were
considered:

\begin{enumerate}
  \item \emph{Collapse (chosen):} All accepted candidates become
    \texttt{att/2} facts regardless of type. Type/confidence are
    preserved as Prolog comments.
  \item \emph{Extended framework:} Use ASPIC+ or Bipolar AF to
    preserve type information in the formal semantics. More expressive,
    but substantially more complex to implement correctly.
  \item \emph{Type-conditioned filtering:} Use separate confidence
    thresholds per attack type before collapsing (e.g., require
    confidence $\geq 80$ for undermining, $\geq 70$ for rebuttal).
\end{enumerate}

We chose option~(1) because: (a) Dung semantics are well-understood and
the implementation is verified; (b) the type information is \emph{not
lost} — it is retained as metadata for analysis; (c) the primary research
question is whether typed prompting \emph{improves extraction quality}
relative to binary prompting, independently of the formal evaluation.
Planned evaluation: typed vs.\ binary prompting will be compared against a
human-annotated gold standard on \texttt{att/2} relations, measuring
precision, recall, and F1.

The resulting Prolog file looks like this:

\begin{lstlisting}[style=prolog]
% arg/1 facts
arg(pro55).  % [pro] Nuclear plants have substantial containment structures.
arg(con72).  % [con] Nuclear energy results in catastrophic env. contamination.

% att/2 facts  (Dung 1995 -- binary; type/conf from LLM candidates as comment)
att(con72, pro55).  % [undermining] conf=80 -- "Catastrophic contamination
                    %   attacks the premise that containment ensures safety."
att(con42, pro106). % [rebuttal]    conf=95 -- "Uranium is limited, directly
                    %   contradicting a persistent supply claim."
\end{lstlisting}

\subsection{Step 3b: Prolog Solver}

The Prolog solver implements all standard Dung semantics~\cite{cerutti2014}:

\begin{itemize}
  \item \textbf{Grounded:} fixed-point iteration of $F_{AF}$ starting from
    $\emptyset$. Polynomial, always terminates.
  \item \textbf{Preferred:} enumeration of maximal admissible sets via
    conflict-free power-set generation. Exponential worst-case; restricted
    to $|\mathcal{A}'| \leq 30$ in the current implementation.
  \item \textbf{Stable:} conflict-free sets that attack all non-members.
    May not exist.
\end{itemize}

The solver is parametrised by the AF source file via a Prolog flag and
returns results as JSON, which the Python driver reads back.

\section{Example Run: Nuclear Energy}
\label{sec:example}

We ran the full pipeline on the UKP nuclear energy test split with a
balanced sample of 10 arguments (5 pro, 5 con). After atomisation, 30
atomic arguments remained. The $\binom{30}{2} = 435$ pairs (minus
same-base-ID pairs: 425) were processed in 43 batches.

\paragraph{Attack statistics.} The pipeline accepted 81 attack relations
out of 425 pairs (19\%). The type distribution is shown in
Table~\ref{tab:types}.

\begin{table}[t]
\caption{Attack type distribution — nuclear energy run (30 atoms,
  425 evaluated pairs).}
\label{tab:types}
\centering
\begin{tabular}{lr}
\toprule
Attack Type  & Share \\
\midrule
undermining  & $\approx$70\% \\
rebuttal     & $\approx$25\% \\
undercutting & $\approx$5\% \\
\midrule
Total (81 accepted) & 100\% \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}\\[4pt]
{\footnotesize Shares estimated from log output; exact per-type counts pending full run.}
\end{table}

\paragraph{Formal result.} The Prolog solver returned the following
extensions:

\begin{lstlisting}[style=prolog]
Grounded  : [con119, con126, con168, con168b, con53,
             con72,  con72b, pro2,   pro55b,  pro5b, pro62]
Preferred : [[con119, con126, con168, con168b, con53,
              con72,  con72b, pro2,   pro55b,  pro5b, pro62]]
Stable    : [[con119, con126, con168, con168b, con53,
              con72,  con72b, pro2,   pro55b,  pro5b, pro62]]
\end{lstlisting}

The unique, identical grounded, preferred, and stable extension indicates
a \emph{well-founded} framework: the attack graph has a clear winner
set with no ambiguity. Of the 11 accepted arguments, 7 are con-stance
and 4 are pro-stance, suggesting the con side is better defended in
this sample.

Selected accepted arguments from the grounded extension:
\begin{itemize}
  \item \textbf{con72:} ``Nuclear energy results in catastrophic
    environmental contamination'' (rebuttal against pro55)
  \item \textbf{con168:} ``Radiation and nuclear waste are difficult
    to manage'' (undermining against multiple pro arguments)
  \item \textbf{pro62:} ``We can make use of solar, wind and other
    renewable sources of energy'' (accepted despite con stance of
    the debate — survives because it is not attacked)
  \item \textbf{pro2:} ``Reactors in the Soviet Union were dangerous,
    but have improved'' (survives; attacks on it are themselves attacked)
\end{itemize}

\section{Design Decisions and Open Questions}
\label{sec:design}

\paragraph{No cross-stance filter.} An earlier version of the pipeline
filtered pairs so that only arguments with opposite stances were checked
for attacks. This was removed because UKP stance labels (\emph{pro}/
\emph{con}) reflect the argument's position in the original text, not a
global debate direction. Same-stance arguments can conflict (e.g., two
pro-nuclear arguments that prioritise incompatible safety strategies).

\paragraph{Confidence calibration.} LLM confidence scores are known to be
poorly calibrated. We treat them as routing signals (accept / verify /
reject) rather than probabilities. The verification step partially
compensates by providing an independent reading for borderline candidates.
A future experiment should measure how often the verifier agrees with the
classifier as a function of the confidence score.

\paragraph{Batch size vs.\ fallback rate.} With batch size $b=10$ and 425
pairs, 43 batch calls are made. However, JSON parse failures trigger
retries, and individual fallback calls for unresolved pairs add
overhead. Observed fallback rate: approximately 20 individual fallback
calls per run ($\approx$5\%).

\paragraph{Scalability.} The preferred-extension solver runs in exponential
worst-case time and is restricted to $|\mathcal{A}'| \leq 30$. For
larger debates, only the grounded extension (polynomial) is computed.
This is a hard constraint that should be addressed before scaling to full
UKP topics.

